# TypeScript Best Practices

## Core Principles

- Prefer type inference over explicit annotations
- Avoid type assertions (`as`) - use type guards and narrowing instead
- Never use `any` - use `unknown` or proper types

## Type Inference

Let TypeScript infer types whenever possible. Use explicit types only for:
- Function parameters (public APIs)
- Complex return types that benefit from documentation
- Discriminated unions for type narrowing

### Use `satisfies` to check without widening

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Preserves literal types
const config = {
  apiUrl: 'https://api.example.com',
  timeout: 5000,
} satisfies { apiUrl: string; timeout: number };

// ❌ Bad - Type assertion loses literal types
const config = {
  apiUrl: 'https://api.example.com',
  timeout: 5000,
} as { apiUrl: string; timeout: number };
```

## Type Narrowing Patterns

### Discriminated unions

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Discriminated union with type narrowing
type AsyncState<T> =
  | { status: 'loading' }
  | { status: 'success'; data: T }
  | { status: 'error'; error: string };

function handleState<T>(state: AsyncState<T>) {
  switch (state.status) {
    case 'loading':
      return 'Loading...';
    case 'success':
      return state.data; // TypeScript knows data exists
    case 'error':
      return state.error; // TypeScript knows error exists
  }
}
```

### Type predicates

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Type predicate function
function isUser(value: unknown): value is User {
  return (
    typeof value === 'object' &&
    value !== null &&
    'id' in value &&
    'name' in value &&
    'email' in value
  );
}
```

## Quick Reference

### Type Inference

- ✅ Let TypeScript infer return types from implementations
- ✅ Infer generic types from usage
- ✅ Use `satisfies` to check types without widening
- ✅ Only add explicit types when necessary for public APIs
- ❌ Don't add redundant type annotations

### Type Assertions

- ✅ Use type guards instead of `as` assertions
- ✅ Validate data before narrowing types
- ✅ Use control flow analysis for type narrowing
- ✅ Prefer `satisfies` over `as` when checking structure
- ❌ Don't use `as` to bypass type checking

### `any` Avoidance

- ✅ Use `unknown` for truly unknown types
- ✅ Define proper interfaces and types
- ✅ Use generics for flexible but type-safe code
- ✅ Use utility types (`Partial`, `Pick`, `Omit`, etc.)
- ❌ Never use `any` - it disables type checking
